<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="562" pageId="4" pageNumber="561" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1366,2041]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,153,251]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="562" pageId="4" pageNumber="561">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,2014,2040]" pageId="4" pageNumber="561">Remarks</emphasis>
. This is the shortest and most robust species among 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Distant" authorityYear="1916" box="[900,1028,2014,2040]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Daimachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="561" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[900,1028,2014,2040]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="561">Daimachus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species so far known. It has a much longer and strongly anteriorly recurved aedeagal shaft. It resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Viraktamath &amp; Webb, 2019" authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2019" box="[923,1062,154,179]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Daimachus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="562" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sirsiensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[923,1062,154,179]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="562">D. sirsiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1071,1159,153,179]" pageId="5" pageNumber="562" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
but has short prong-like lateral projections on the apex of the aedeagal shaft compared to long thin processes in the latter species and also lacks the subapical ventral projection found in the latter species.
</paragraph>
